SIMPLE: extension
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Extension
<hw>Ex*ten"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>extensio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>extension</ets>. See <er>Extend</er>,
<pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of extending or the
state of being extended; a stretching out; enlargement in breadth or
continuation of length; increase; augmentation; expansion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>That property of a body by
which it occupies a portion of space.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Logic & Metaph.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Capacity
of a concept or general term to include a greater or smaller number of
objects; -- correlative of <contr>intension</contr>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>the class or set of objects to which a term refers; -- contrasted
with <contr>intension</contr>, the logical specification which defines
members of a class, being the set of attributes which are necessary and
sufficient to recognize an object as a member of the class.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The law is that the intension of our knowledge is in the inverse
ratio of its <qex>extension</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>extension</qex> of [the term] plant is greater than that
of geranium, because it includes more objects.</q> <rj><qau>Abp.
Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Surg.)</fld> <def>The operation of stretching a
broken bone so as to bring the fragments into the same straight
line.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>The straightening of a limb,
in distinction from <contr>flexion</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Com.)</fld> <def>A written engagement on the part
of a creditor, allowing a debtor further time to pay a debt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Counter extension</b></col>. <fld>(Surg.)</fld> <cd>See
under <er>Counter</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Extension table</b></col>, <cd>a
table so constructed as to be readily extended or contracted in
length.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Extensional</ent>⟦br⟧
